<ArticleLayout
  title="Bathroom Storage Products Worth Considering"
  description="Practical bathroom storage ideas for Australian homes, apartments and rentals, including vanity storage, shower organisation, towel storage and small-space product choices."
  category="Bathroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  image="/images/bathroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy bathroom with warm finishes, practical storage and soft natural light"
>
  <p>
    Bathrooms are often small, busy rooms that need to hold more than they comfortably can.
    Towels, toiletries, cleaning products, hair tools, spare toilet paper, skincare, medicines
    and bath products can quickly make the space feel cluttered.
  </p>
  <p>
    In many Australian homes, the bathroom also has limited built-in storage. Older homes may
    have a small vanity, apartments may have little floor space, and rentals may restrict
    drilling or permanent shelving. That means bathroom storage needs to be practical,
    moisture-resistant and suited to the way the room is actually used.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers bathroom storage products worth considering for a more organised and
    easier-to-use bathroom.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what should stay in the bathroom</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying storage products, it helps to decide what actually belongs in the bathroom.
  </p>
  <p>Useful bathroom items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Everyday toiletries.</li>
    <li>Toothbrushes and toothpaste.</li>
    <li>Skincare used daily.</li>
    <li>Hair products used regularly.</li>
    <li>Towels and hand towels.</li>
    <li>Toilet paper.</li>
    <li>Basic cleaning products.</li>
    <li>Bath items if the bathroom has a bath.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Other items may not need to live there. Bulk supplies, rarely used products, old skincare,
    expired medicine, extra makeup and unopened gift sets can take up valuable space.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small bathroom works best when everyday items are easy to reach and occasional items are
    stored elsewhere.
  </p>

  <h2>Use vanity storage properly</h2>
  <p>
    The vanity is usually the main bathroom storage area, but it can become messy quickly.
    Deep cupboards under the sink often waste space because plumbing makes the area awkward.
  </p>
  <p>Useful vanity storage products include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Small baskets.</li>
    <li>Stackable drawers.</li>
    <li>Pull-out organisers.</li>
    <li>Clear tubs.</li>
    <li>Shelf risers.</li>
    <li>Cleaning product caddies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Grouping items by task can make the vanity easier to use. For example, keep daily
    skincare in one container, hair products in another and cleaning supplies in a separate
    caddy.
  </p>
  <p>
    If children use the bathroom, avoid storing sharp items, medicines or strong cleaning
    products within easy reach.
  </p>

  <h2>Add drawer dividers for small items</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom drawers can quickly fill with small loose items. Drawer dividers can help keep
    things visible and easier to find.
  </p>
  <p>They work well for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Toothbrush heads.</li>
    <li>Razors.</li>
    <li>Hair ties.</li>
    <li>Clips.</li>
    <li>Makeup.</li>
    <li>Nail care items.</li>
    <li>Contact lens supplies.</li>
    <li>Small skincare products.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Adjustable dividers are useful because bathroom drawers vary in size. Clear trays can also
    work well because they make it easy to see what is inside.
  </p>
  <p>
    The goal is not to make the drawer look perfect. The goal is to stop small items from
    sliding around and disappearing under each other.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep shower products contained</h2>
  <p>
    Shampoo, conditioner, body wash, razors and face cleansers can make the shower look
    cluttered if they sit on the floor or edges.
  </p>
  <p>Useful shower storage options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Hanging shower caddies.</li>
    <li>Corner shower shelves.</li>
    <li>Suction shower baskets.</li>
    <li>Adhesive shower shelves.</li>
    <li>Over-screen organisers.</li>
    <li>Refillable pump bottles.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    In rentals, avoid drilling into tiles unless you have permission. Adhesive or suction
    options can work, but they need to suit the surface and weight of the products.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying a shower organiser, check how much weight it can hold and whether it will be
    exposed to direct water. Products that trap water can become harder to clean.
  </p>

  <h2>Use wall storage carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Wall storage can be helpful in small bathrooms, but it needs to be chosen carefully. Too
    much wall storage can make a bathroom feel crowded.
  </p>
  <p>Useful wall storage products include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Wall-mounted cabinets.</li>
    <li>Floating shelves.</li>
    <li>Towel hooks.</li>
    <li>Toilet paper holders.</li>
    <li>Small rails.</li>
    <li>Over-toilet shelving.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Closed cabinets are often better for products that create visual clutter. Open shelves
    work best for neat items like folded towels, a small plant or a few everyday products.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the bathroom is narrow, check that shelves will not stick out too far. Storage should
    make the room easier to use, not make it harder to move around.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider over-toilet storage</h2>
  <p>
    The wall area above the toilet is often unused. In a small bathroom, it can be a practical
    place for extra storage.
  </p>
  <p>Possible uses include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Spare toilet paper.</li>
    <li>Hand towels.</li>
    <li>Small baskets.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
    <li>Extra soap.</li>
    <li>Bathroom sprays.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Over-toilet storage can be wall-mounted or freestanding. Freestanding units may suit
    renters, but they need to be stable and sized correctly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing heavy or fragile items above the toilet. Lightweight baskets and everyday
    supplies are usually more practical.
  </p>

  <h2>Use hooks instead of towel rails where space is tight</h2>
  <p>
    Traditional towel rails can take up a lot of wall space. Hooks may be more practical in
    small bathrooms, shared bathrooms or family homes.
  </p>
  <p>Hooks can hold:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Bath towels.</li>
    <li>Hand towels.</li>
    <li>Robes.</li>
    <li>Hair towels.</li>
    <li>Shower caps.</li>
    <li>Toiletry bags.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Hooks also make it easier for children to hang towels compared with folding them neatly
    over a rail.
  </p>
  <p>
    The downside is that towels may not dry as evenly on hooks, especially in damp bathrooms.
    If airflow is poor, a rail or heated towel ladder may work better.
  </p>

  <h2>Store spare towels outside the bathroom if needed</h2>
  <p>
    Many bathrooms do not have enough space for a full towel cupboard. If storage is tight,
    keep only the towels currently being used in the bathroom and store spares elsewhere.
  </p>
  <p>Good locations for spare towels may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Linen cupboard.</li>
    <li>Bedroom wardrobe.</li>
    <li>Laundry cupboard.</li>
    <li>Hallway storage.</li>
    <li>Under-bed storage.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If towels must stay in the bathroom, use a cabinet, basket or shelf that keeps them away
    from direct moisture.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep cleaning products easy to access</h2>
  <p>
    Bathrooms need regular cleaning, so it helps to keep basic cleaning supplies nearby.
    However, cleaning products should be stored safely and neatly.
  </p>
  <p>A simple bathroom cleaning caddy might include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Bathroom spray.</li>
    <li>Glass cleaner.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
    <li>Scrub brush.</li>
    <li>Toilet cleaner.</li>
    <li>Disposable or washable gloves.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keeping these items together makes cleaning easier and reduces the chance of bottles
    being scattered across multiple cupboards.
  </p>
  <p>
    If young children or pets can access the bathroom, store cleaning products higher up or
    behind a child-safe latch.
  </p>

  <h2>Use clear containers for daily products</h2>
  <p>
    Clear containers can be helpful for everyday bathroom products because they make items
    easy to see. This is useful for shared bathrooms where multiple people use the same vanity
    or shelves.
  </p>
  <p>Clear containers may suit:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Skincare.</li>
    <li>Hair products.</li>
    <li>Dental care.</li>
    <li>Makeup.</li>
    <li>Bath products.</li>
    <li>Travel-size items.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For a calmer look, avoid filling every visible shelf with containers. Use clear storage
    inside cupboards or drawers where visibility matters most.
  </p>

  <h2>Create a system for overflow products</h2>
  <p>
    Bathrooms often collect half-used products. Having an overflow system can stop products
    from multiplying across shelves and drawers.
  </p>
  <p>A simple approach is to keep one small basket for backup items such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Spare toothpaste.</li>
    <li>Extra soap.</li>
    <li>Replacement razors.</li>
    <li>Spare shampoo.</li>
    <li>Toilet paper.</li>
    <li>Skincare refills.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    When the basket is full, avoid buying more until something is used. This can help reduce
    waste and stop the bathroom from becoming overstocked.
  </p>

  <h2>What to check before buying bathroom storage products</h2>
  <p>Before buying bathroom organisers, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The size of the bathroom.</li>
    <li>Whether the product suits wet areas.</li>
    <li>Whether it needs drilling.</li>
    <li>Whether it can be cleaned easily.</li>
    <li>Whether it will rust.</li>
    <li>Whether it solves a real storage problem.</li>
    <li>Whether it suits renters if you are renting.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Bathroom storage products should be practical in a damp room. Materials matter. Metal
    products should resist rust, timber should be sealed or kept dry, and fabric storage
    should not sit where it will absorb moisture.
  </p>

  <h2>Final thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    The best bathroom storage products are the ones that make everyday routines easier. A good
    setup keeps daily items within reach, stores spare products neatly and avoids cluttering
    the room with storage that does not suit the space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start with the biggest frustration. That might be a messy vanity, crowded shower, nowhere
    for towels or too many products on the bench. Improve one area at a time, and the bathroom
    will feel more organised without needing a renovation.
  </p>

